The paper presents a new model for multimodal journey planning in public transport networks, which involves the use of algorithms and data structures to efficiently compute and update journey plans in real-time. This suggests that the paper could be relevant to several sub-categories of computer science, including artificial intelligence (cs.AI) for the development of intelligent journey planning systems, machine learning (cs.LG) for the use of data-driven approaches to optimize journey plans, data structures (cs.DS) for the efficient storage and retrieval of timetable information, robotics (cs.RO) for the integration of autonomous vehicles into the transport network, and social and information networks (cs.SI) for the analysis of passenger behavior and network dynamics.
